Here's a complete implementation for a C# MCP server wrapping a REST API via stdio transport.

---

### 1. Scaffold the project

```bash
dotnet new mcpserver -n MyApiMcpServer
cd MyApiMcpServer
```

If the template isn't installed: `dotnet new install Microsoft.McpServer.ProjectTemplates`

---

### 2. Tool class — `ApiTools.cs`

```csharp
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;

[McpServerToolType]
public class ApiTools(HttpClient httpClient, ILogger<ApiTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Get a user by ID from the REST API.")]
    public async Task<string> GetUser(
        [Description("The numeric user ID")] int userId,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching user {UserId}", userId);
        var json = await httpClient.GetStringAsync($"/users/{userId}", cancellationToken);
        return json;
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("List all posts, optionally filtered by user ID.")]
    public async Task<string> ListPosts(
        [Description("Filter posts by this user ID (optional)")] int? userId = null,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var url = userId.HasValue ? $"/posts?userId={userId}" : "/posts";
        logger.LogInformation("Listing posts: {Url}", url);
        var json = await httpClient.GetStringAsync(url, cancellationToken);
        return json;
    }

    [McpServerTool(ReadOnly = false), Description("Create a new post.")]
    public async Task<string> CreatePost(
        [Description("Title of the post")] string title,
        [Description("Body content of the post")] string body,
        [Description("Author user ID")] int authorId,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var payload = JsonSerializer.Serialize(new { title, body, userId = authorId });
        var content = new StringContent(payload, System.Text.Encoding.UTF8, "application/json");
        var response = await httpClient.PostAsync("/posts", content, cancellationToken);
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync(cancellationToken);
    }
}
```

---

### 3. `Program.cs` — stdio transport

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: log to stderr only — stdout is the JSON-RPC channel
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

builder.Services.AddHttpClient<ApiTools>(client =>
{
    client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com");
});

builder.Services.AddMcpServer(options =>
{
    options.ServerInfo = new() { Name = "MyApiMcpServer", Version = "1.0.0" };
})
.WithStdioServerTransport()
.WithToolsFromAssembly();

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

---

### 4. How DI works for MCP tools

The SDK supports **two injection styles**:

| Style | Class type | How services are injected |
|---|---|---|
| **Constructor injection** | Non-static class | Services in the primary constructor (like `HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`) |
| **Method parameter injection** | Static class | DI services as method parameters alongside tool parameters |

**Key rule:** The SDK automatically distinguishes tool parameters from DI services. Only parameters with `[Description]` appear in the tool's JSON schema exposed to the LLM. Services like `HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`, `CancellationToken`, `IMcpServer`, and `IProgress<>` are resolved from DI and **never** exposed to the LLM.

In the example above, `ApiTools` uses **constructor injection** via a primary constructor — `HttpClient` and `ILogger<ApiTools>` are injected once when the class is instantiated. `AddHttpClient<ApiTools>(...)` registers a typed `HttpClient` with the base address pre-configured, so every tool method shares it.

Build and verify with:

```bash
dotnet build
dotnet run
```

The process will start and wait for JSON-RPC input on stdin — that means it's working.
